		<description><![CDATA[The scam : Computer users have to take precautions to protect their hard drives from spam and malware. One of the more common programs to protect computers is Spybot S &#38; D (search and destroy.) If you use it, Scambusters says, beware an e-mail that appears to come from the producers of this software offering [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The scam : Computer users have to take precautions to protect their hard drives from spam and malware. One of the more common programs to protect computers is Spybot S &amp; D (search and destroy.) If you use it, Scambusters says, beware an e-mail that appears to come from the producers of this software offering an upgrade to &#8221;Spybot 2009&#8221; or &#8221;Spybot Protection 2009.&#8221;</p>
<p>How it works: You receive an e-mail, which may also arrive in your inbox as spam even if you don&#8217;t have the original software, which provides a download link hosted in Panama. Various reports say that the program is either a rip-off of the original or it contains malware, Scambusters says.</p>
<p>What to do: Most programs, including Spybot, automatically check for updates or have an item in their help menu that allows you to do this manually, Scambusters says. If you get an e-mail offering updates for any software, don&#8217;t click the link but go to the producer&#8217;s official home page by keying in the URL, they say.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, this kind of scam has been around for a long time and Internet thieves have been coming up with new fake sites for as long as online police have been trying to take them down. You also may find bogus download sites for Ad-Aware, another spyware remover. Be careful.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.mcall.com/news/local/bethlehem/all-b3_5yback1211.6685539dec11,0,762193.story?track=rss" target="_blank">[Read More]</a></p>
]]></content:encoded>
